      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# **Project Name**    - **Global Terrorism Database Analysis: 1970-2017**\n",
        "\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "vncDsAP0Gaoa"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# **Project Summary -**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "FJNUwmbgGyua"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## Project Summary: Global Terrorism Analysis\n",
        "* Overview\n",
        "  * This project performed an Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) on the Global Terrorism Database to identify patterns in how, where, and why attacks occur. By analyzing nearly 50,000 historical records, we transformed raw data into actionable insights for security and risk management.\n",
        "\n",
        "* Data Cleaning & Context\n",
        "  * Before the analysis, we cleaned the data by fixing missing values and correcting corrupted geographical coordinates. A key finding was that our dataset focuses heavily on the period between 1970 and 2005. This means the insights reflect historical 20th-century conflicts—such as those in Latin America and Western Europe—rather than modern-day events in the Middle East.\n",
        "\n",
        "* Key Findings\n",
        "  * Through different visualizations, we discovered three major trends:\n",
        "\n",
        "   1. Geography: Terrorism was not global but concentrated in \"Hotspots.\" South America (Colombia and Peru) and South Asia were the most targeted regions in this dataset.\n",
        "\n",
        "   2. Tactics: Bombings were the most frequent method used (40%), but Firearms resulted in the highest total number of casualties.\n",
        "\n",
        "   3. Targets: Private Citizens and Businesses were targeted more often than the military or police. This highlights that terrorism is frequently used to cause economic damage and public fear.\n",
        "\n",
        "* Business Impact\n",
        "  * Our analysis provides a clear strategy for the client:\n",
        "\n",
        "   1. Targeted Funding: Invest security resources specifically in the identified \"Hotspot\" regions rather than spreading them thin.\n",
        "\n",
        "   2. Tactic Defense: Prioritize building reinforcements and detection systems for explosives and firearms.\n",
        "\n",
        "   3. Private-Sector Safety: Since businesses are high-priority targets, corporations must invest in specialized security and emergency medical response plans."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "F6v_1wHtG2nS"
      }
    },
