      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "* I chose a Pair Plot because it provides a comprehensive bird's-eye view of the entire dataset's numerical relationships. It combines Univariate analysis (the histograms/KDEs on the diagonal) with Bivariate analysis (the scatter plots on the off-diagonal), allowing us to spot patterns, clusters, and outliers across all variables simultaneously."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "eMmPjTByveiU"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "##### 2. What is/are the insight(s) found from the chart?"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "22aHeOlLveiV"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "* Skewed Distributions: The diagonal plots show that Killed, Wounded, and Total_Casualties are \"heavy-tailed\"—meaning most attacks have low casualties, but a few extreme events (outliers) stretch the data significantly.\n",
        "\n",
        "* Correlated Growth: The scatter plots between Killed and Total_Casualties show a tight linear cluster, confirming that deaths are the primary driver of the casualty metric.\n",
        "\n",
        "* Temporal Spread: The scatter plots involving Year show that while the volume of data points increases in later years (up to 2005), the intensity of individual attacks (the height of the dots) remains inconsistently spread, indicating no simple \"year-over-year\" predictability in attack severity."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "uPQ8RGwHveiV"
      }
